COMIC BOOK READING LIST


The definitive Franco-Belgian reading list - Part 1 - Crime/Noir

I'm French, and I've been raised with bandes dessinées. I've answered in length to this query earlier and was told to make a topic here. I'm not sure everything has been translated in English, I'll do my best, as well as including other suggestions. Please give me suggestions if you can, I will add them.
Crime

The indisputable king is Jean Van Hamme. If you got only one series to read, it's XIII.

    XIII : a seminal series, drawn mainly by William Vance, on a conspiracy involving the assassination of POTUS. It's the canvas for Ludlum's Jason Bourne novels. It's probably the best French crime series you can ever read up until The Judgment, the 13th issue. After that, it's still an OK read but compared to the beginning it's flushed down the toilet.

    Largo Winch : aka Van Hamme's other series, involving a trust fund kid whose dad is murdered one day and finds himself at the head of one of the largest conglomerates on Earth. It's Batman if he was an accountant : he's handsome, filthy rich, and everybody is always trying to kill him to get his money. There's a trustee sidekick met in a Turkish jail, outlandish plots, grotesque bad guys, naked women with model curves every other page. Clearly Van Hamme's guilty pleasure, but it's still top-notch.

    Wayne Shelton : Light Largo Winch if he was Thief of Thieves. Still Van Hamme, still a handsome hero, still women, still outlandish plots except he's a thief. I like it but it's clearly a one-read.

    SODA : Written by Tome, the guy who took Spirou after Franquin's death in the 80s. It's got clear elements from issues like Vito la Déveine . Happening in a caricature version of NYC, with a cop whose mom believes he's a preacher and has to change clothes in the elevator but looks like a receding hairline version of Cobra while on duty. He's got a depressed chief trying to channel his neurosis into a pet goldfish, the aforementioned mother and overall fantastic plots. It reads fast and is truly amazing.

    Blacksad by Guarnido. No introduction needed. Anthropomorphic cat, noir atmosphere, trench coats, bad guys.

    The Black Order Brigade and its follow-up, Hunting Party by Bilal & Christin. I'll make a dedicated section for them in the scifi segment of my answer, but everything by Bilal is almost required read and this is no exception. Both are political thrillers about old timers gathering one last time and mustering their memories, one in 1936 Spain with the International Brigades, the other from the Soviet Politburo around 1983. Both deal with disillusionment, trodden dreams and the bitterness that comes with age when the dream you believed in ends broken in the flow of time.

    Albany & Sturgess : Drawn by Floc'h, it's a classic ligne claire 4-issues series in the style of Tintin, with a protagonist duo investigating during the roaring 20s. Floc'h is a menswear and cinema fanatic and that shows : every character is impeccably dressed. It's notable for having one of the first strong female protagonists in the shape of Olivia Sturgess, the second half of the siblings duo, an aristocratic suffragette. Each issue is an homage to different movies, with the first one, Le Rendez-vous de Sevenoaks being my favorite but standing out a bit. It's a weird British riff on Carpenter's Mouth of Madness featuring a rando writer who realizes one day he's the protagonist of an immortal horror theatre writer from the 20s.

    The Black Dahlia is an adaptation of the James Ellroy novel from Miles Hyman, one of the best charcoal illustrators of the last decade, with striking colors and contrast.

    Nestor Burma by Tardi. An adaptation of Léo St-Clair's novels by Tardi, very reminiscent of the classic Maigret series by Simenon or Michel Audiard's movies like Les Tontons Flingueurs. Imho not on the level of Adèle Blanc-Sec or Brindavoine, but if you're looking for a good crime series dripping with atmosphere, dirty Parisian dives, sloppy streets, and gangsters in trench coats and slim ties in a 50s setting, you're in for a treat.

    The Crow (Le Choucas) by Lax. This is great. The graphism is reminiscent of Italian artists who worked on Dylan Dog like Francesco Dossena, dry, angular. Follows a chain-smoking, cinema amateur, watchmaker nicknamed the Crow because of his yellow shirts and black suits who gets fired on Christmas' Eve when electronic clocks supersede mechanical ones, and decides to become a private eye.

    The Amazing and Depressing Investigations of Inspector Canardo by Benoît Sokal, the guy who did the Amerzone. I'm not even kidding that's the full French title you can find in some publications. I love this series. It follows a full-on breakdown and alcoholic duck who got fired from the force and haphazardly begins a career as a gumshoe, and always finds himself in over his head. It's Blacksad if Blacksad was a loser firing on only one cylinder.

    The Corsican File (L'Enquête Corse) by Pétillon. Created by the political cartoonist Pétillon, it follows a parody of private eye, Jack Palmer, going to investigate a inheritance case in Corsica. It's hilarious but relies heavily on previous knowledge of the local situation : Corsica has a long and complicated history with French mainland, with half the island wishing they could secede and the other one prenant le maquis (going underground) because of their ties to separatist movements. I suggest you read Asterix in Corsica first if you want to get in the know.

    Guardrails (Garde-Fous) by Bézian, the guy who did Adam Sarlech. Magnificent riff on Agatha Christie with a couple of rich socialites throwing a party in a remote location and learning there might be a serial killer in their midst. Claustrophobic af.

    Black Water Lillies from Cassegrain. One-shot featuring murders in Giverny, a small countryside village where Monet painted his eponymous Nympheas. It's masterfully constructed in 3 different paintings alongside the story in an impressionistic style. I'd put it on the level of Peeter's work on Aâma in indie crime.

    Berceuse Assassine (Murder Lullaby), again by Tome (the Spirou and SODA scenarist I mentioned up there), follows a stringed up taxi driver who decides to get rid of his disabled harpy of a wife.

    Bullet to the Head from Matz, got a forgettable Stallone adaptation in 2012. The comics is way better and is about two hitmen roaming around a city trying to fulfill a contract only to get themselves unwillingly embroidered in a political scandal.

    The Killer, another one by Matz, regularly recommended, who follows the life of a unnamed assassin and his inner monologue. It's peculiar but good.

    Green Manor is a hilarious take on Sherlock Holmes - like fiction, with a string of murders centered around a Victorian club which seems to have a knack to attract maniacs.

    Murena by Dufaux. Political thriller set in Ancient Rome, chronicles the rise and fall of Neron through the eyes of a fictional protagonist. Really well-drawn and written.

    Malone from Rio. In the same vein as Matz' works, follows a chess match between a killer and the cop hunting him, one waiting for the other to do a mistake.


